  Brad Crandall wrote WHOA! for 12-MHz machines, and although the
  program works on faster machines as well, it doesn't slow down them
  enough. So I reassembled WHOA!.ASM on and for my 16-MHz machine in
  order to find out an appropriate optimum value for 16-MHz. After
  many trials (and rebootings) I winded up with a maximum value of
  -520 (slowest rate). This value decreases the speed of my system
  drastically; to disable SLOWA via hotkey ALT-F10 can take up to a
  minute ≠. For most graphic applications a value between -480 and
  -510 will do fine.

  I have tested SLOWA with several graphic applications and demos -
  with good results. If you have a 16-MHz machine use SLOWA instead of
  WHOA!. I don't know, whether and how SLOWA works on faster machines.
  If you operate a faster one use SLOWA on your own risks.

  Except for slower values SLOWA behaves the same way as WHOA!
  described above and in WHOA!.DOC. Use DAZ16.BAT as a demo and
  calibrate DAZZLER down to a level at your likings. DAZ16.DAT (or
  DAZ12.BAT) can easily be modified for other applications, just
  change the batch line

  DAZZLER
  ~~~~~~~
  to the name of your program. When running at an extreme slow level
  some applications tend occasionally to blank the screen. Pressing
  the space bar will keep them going in most cases.


